Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board, one candidate tactical move for Black is to bring the knight from c6 to d4. This is interesting because from d4 the knight not only lands on a central square but it also directly attacks the White queen on e2. Moreover, from d4 it eyes the pawn on c2. If White does not capture the knight immediately, Black may have the resource of …Nc2+ on a future move, forking the White king on e1 and the rook on a1. (Of course, White may try to avoid the fork by capturing the knight, but that would require giving up the queen and isn’t optimal.)

Thus, I choose to play:

make_move c6d4

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board setup, one strong candidate is to activate your queen with a checking move. For example, moving your queen from c1 to d2 (in UCI format “c1d2”) puts White’s king on f2 in check along the entire second rank. The move has several advantages:

• It immediately forces White to respond.
• It restricts the White king’s options (its adjacent squares along rank 2 become controlled by your queen).
• It keeps your queen safe from immediate capture since it lands far enough from the White king.

Thus, as Black, a good move is:

make_move c1d2

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Proxy (to Player_Black):

Based on the current position:

• Black’s pieces: King on c3; Queen on g5; Pawns on f5, g6, and h7.
• White’s only piece is the King on f3.

A move that immediately checks the white king while ensuring that the queen cannot be captured is to bring the queen down along the g‑file – namely, from g5 to g4. After Qg5–g4 the white king is in check (since f3 and g4 are diagonally adjacent) yet if White tries to capture the queen by Kxg4 the pawn sitting on f5 covers that square (because a pawn on f5 attacks g4). (Other adjacent escapes exist for White—but none allow an immediate capture of the queen.) 

Thus, a strong candidate is to play:

  make_move g5g4

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll play the move  f2f1 —that is, move the queen from f2 down to f1, giving check to the white king. 

To explain briefly in the position (assuming the board is read with rank 8 on top and rank 1 at the bottom, so that white’s king sits on h1):

• Black’s queen is on f2 and white’s king sits in the corner on h1, whose only neighboring squares are g1, g2, and h2.
• By playing f2→f1, the queen moves vertically and lands on f1. On f1 the queen controls all of rank 1 as well as its diagonals.
• In particular, the king on h1 is checked. It cannot go to g1 because that square lies on rank 1 (attacked by the queen), and it cannot go to g2 because g2 lies on the queen’s up‐right diagonal (from f1 to g2). The only legal reply is moving the king to h2.
• Although this isn’t mate in one—the white king escapes to h2—it forces a very constrained reply and paves the way for a quick mate. In the ensuing winning king–queen endgame, Black will be able to drive the white king into an ever tighter net.

So my move is: make_move f2f1

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board as provided (after interpreting the top row as rank 1 so that White’s only piece—the ♔—sits on h1 and Black’s key pieces lie on f2 (♛), e3 (♚) and g3 (♟)), notice that White’s king is currently “locked in” (its three adjacent squares g1, g2 and h2 are all covered by the Black queen on f2). Although it’s not in check now, if Black were to “pass” then White would have no legal moves—and the game would be drawn by stalemate.

To avoid stalemate and to force a win, Black must give a check while “uncovering” one escape square (so that if White must move, a mate can be delivered on the next move). One very effective resource is to move the queen to f1. In that case the queen moves from f2 to f1. Now White’s king on h1 is in check along rank 1 (since the queen on f1 controls the entire first rank). Its available adjacent squares (g1, g2, and h2) are all covered:
 • g1 is attacked along the first rank by the queen.
 • g2 is attacked diagonally (since f1→g2 is a one‑step diagonal).
 • h2 is covered by Black’s pawn on g3 (since from g3 a Black pawn attacks g3’s “forward” diagonals – here, h2 is one of them).

Thus, after Qf2–f1 the White king has no legal move to escape the check, meaning that move delivers mate.

So as Black, the winning move is:

make_move f2f1

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Proxy (to Player_Black):

Failed to make move: illegal uci: 'f2f1' in 7K/5q2/4k1p1/8/8/8/8/8 b - - 5 93

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll now play as Black. In the current position the White king on h8 is “locked in” by the Black queen on f7—even though it isn’t in check at the moment (its three adjacent squares g8, g7, and h7 are all covered by the queen). If Black were to make a “waiting move” (for example, moving the king or pawn) then White would have no legal moves on its turn and the game would be drawn by stalemate.

To convert this stalemate “trap” into a win, Black must give check in a way that “unlocks” an escape square for White so that White is forced to move and then Black can continue with the winning plan. (In the similar “mate‐in‐1” pattern from an inverted board, the winning move was Qf2→f1—but after a 180° rotation with White’s king on h8, Black’s queen on f7, Black’s king on e6 and pawn on g6, the analogous move becomes Qf7→f8.)

Let’s look at the move 1…Qf7–f8:

• After 1…Qf8+, the queen lands on f8 (file f, rank8). Now she gives check along the 8th rank.
• White’s king (currently on h8) must move and its only legal adjacent squares are:
 – g8 (which is attacked by the queen on f8 along rank8),
 – g7 (which is attacked by the queen on f8 along its southeast diagonal),
 – h7 (which is not attacked by the queen on f8).
• Hence, White must play 2.Kh7.

(Once the White king leaves h8, the stalemate is broken. Black will then be able to force mate in the following moves.)

Thus, to avoid stalemate and keep the winning advantage, my move is:

make_move f7f8

Our black pawn on c3 (located on square c3) currently sits on rank 3, and by moving it one square forward (to square c2, i.e. rank 2), it’ll be only one move away from promotion. Given that White’s only pieces—a lone pawn on a3 and a king on h1—are too far away to immediately interfere, advancing the c‐pawn is an excellent way to pressure the position.

I therefore choose to play:

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I’ll play  Qg3–d3 which is a horizontal queen move from g3 to d3. (In UCI notation that’s “g3d3”.)

On our board the queen on d3 checks the white king along the diagonal (d3–e2–f1); importantly, from d3 the queen is not adjacent to the white king so it cannot be captured immediately. White’s king then has only a few escape squares (for example, e1, f2, g1, or g2), but none of these stops black from steadily improving the position. 

I now complete my turn with:

make_move g3d3

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board, a promising candidate is to use our queen on f3 to issue a check that limits the white king’s escape options. One move to consider is moving the queen one square down to f2. In algebraic (UCI) notation that move is:

make_move f3f2

After Qf2 the queen controls all of rank 2 and key diagonals from f2. In particular, with the white king on h2 its neighboring squares are:

 • g1 (attacked diagonally from f2 via the SW diagonal: f2→g1),
 • g2 (attacked along rank 2),
 • g3 (attacked on the NE diagonal: f2→g3),
 • along with h2 being the king’s current square under check,
 • The only squares that remain for the white king to try are h1 and h3.

Also note that unlike some other checking moves (for example, Qg2, Qh1, or Qh3) where the queen would be adjacent and available for capture, Qf2 is not capturable directly by the king. (The white king on h2 cannot jump two squares to capture on f2.) 

Thus Qf2 (f3→f2) appears to be a strong move and puts immediate pressure on White. 

I'll now play:

make_move f3f2

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position, one promising approach is to safeguard our kingside pawn that’s immediately targeted. Notice that the white queen on d1 eyes the pawn on h5 via the diagonal d1–e2–f3–g4–h5. If we allow white to capture that pawn, we’ll already be down material. On the other hand, the pawn on a4 is also attacked (along d1–c2–b3–a4), but we cannot easily save both in one move.

A natural idea is to move our king so that it defends one of the attacked pawns. Moving our king from f5 to g5 (UCI: “f5g5”) does exactly that: from g5, the king’s adjacent squares include h5 so that pawn becomes defended. We then anticipate that white will capture the undefended pawn on a4 with Qxa4. Although we lose that pawn, our kingside structure (with the h5 pawn now safely guarded by the king and the h4 pawn still in place) may offer better practical drawing chances in this queen-versus-pawns endgame.

Thus, our chosen move is:

make_move f5g5

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I’ll play a knight maneuver that unblocks my bishop’s deadly diagonal while eyeing a potential fork. My move is to re‐deploy the knight from f3 to d4 (i.e. “f3d4”). 

That move has two ideas:
1. By vacating f3, the bishop on d5 will then have a clear line along d5–e4–f3–g2–h1. (If White were to “idle,” I’d capture the queen on h1.)
2. The knight landing on d4 is actively centralized and will, on a future move, have access to b3 (or c2), eyeing White’s rook on a1 (and even the bishop on c1).

Of course, a good opponent can try to parry the threat – for example, by interposing White’s knight from g1 to f3 to block the bishop’s line or by shifting the queen. But in my estimation the move  f3d4  creates tactical problems that I hope will pay off.

So I’ll now complete my turn with: 

make_move f3d4

Based on the current board, one candidate move is to use the black queen on g3 to capture the white pawn on d3. This move (in UCI notation "g3d3") does a few things:
• It picks up a pawn.
• Although d3 is adjacent to the white king on c2, the square d3 is defended by the black bishop on c4 (since bishop on c4 controls the southeast diagonal, including d3). This prevents the white king from safely capturing the queen.
• The queen’s move from g3 to d3 is legal along the third rank and helps centralize your queen.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position, one candidate move is to mobilize the active rook. (Recall that our black rook on c4 is very well‐placed in this position.) For example, moving the rook down the c–file to c2 puts pressure on white’s rook on a2 (since the a2–c2 corridor is now open).

This move – 1…Rc2 – has a two‐fold idea. First, it directly eyes the white rook along rank 2; white will have to decide whether to move that piece or even risk capturing our rook. (If white does capture on c2 with the rook, trading rooks, then even though we lose our rook, we’ll be left with our bishop and six extra pawns versus white’s lone pawn—a winning endgame for black.) On the other hand, if white retreats the rook, we have forced it to lose a tempo and can later coordinate our extra material to press home the advantage.

With our huge material edge (a king, six pawns, a bishop and a rook versus white’s king, rook and pawn), converting to a won endgame is only a matter of technique. Mobilizing our rook with …Rc2 forces white’s hand and simplifies the position further.

I therefore choose to play:

make_move c4c2

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll go ahead and promote my pawn. My move is:

make_move e2e1q

Here's my reasoning:

• I notice that my pawn on e2 is already one step from the promotion square (e1). If I promote it to a queen immediately, I create enormous counterplay against white.
• White’s rook on h1 can capture on e1, but trading the extra queen for the rook simply exchanges some firepower. After 2.Rxe1 the material would be: I’d have my rook along with my remaining pawns (on a7, f7, g7, and h7), while white would be left with just their rook and pawn. That extra pawn majority (4 pawns versus a lone h‑pawn) should lead to a winning endgame.
• In any continuation, if white declines the capture, I get a full queen—a far more powerful piece.
  
Thus, even though the promoted queen on e1 falls quickly if captured, the ensuing rook endgame favors Black’s extra pawns and overall material edge.

I therefore play 1... e2e1=Q.

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Proxy (to Player_Black):

Move made, switching player

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, here’s what we see after translating the diagram into UCI coordinates (with the top printed row corresponding to rank 8 and the bottom printed row to rank 1):

• Black’s pieces are:
 – King on f8 (row 1, column 6 → f8)
 – Pawn on a7 (row 2, column 1 → a7)
 – Pawns on f7, g7, h7 (row 2, columns 6, 7, 8 → f7, g7, h7)
 – Queen on a1 (row 8, column 1 → a1)

• White’s only piece is the King on b3 (row 6, column 2 → b3).

It is Black’s turn. A natural idea is to use the queen (currently on a1) to deliver a check while cutting off escape squares. One promising move is to play Qb2 (UCI: a1b2). This move is along the one‐step diagonal from a1 to b2 and puts White’s king on b3 in check. After Qb2 the queen controls:
 – File b (all squares b1–b8)
 – Rank 2 (all squares a2–h2)
 – Diagonals from b2 (up–right: c3, d4, …; and up–left: a3)

A quick look at the adjacent squares for the White king (from b3, its one‐step moves are to a2, a3, a4, b2, b4, c2, c3, c4) shows that after Qb2 at least two squares remain available (a4 and c4, which are not covered by the queen’s lines). (Other queen moves like Qa2 or Qc3 would similarly deliver check, but Qb2 looks natural in this context.)

Thus, as Black, I choose to play:

make_move a1b2

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, I notice that Black’s only pieces are the king on d4, the queen on e5, and the pawns on f4 and g4. White only has a lone king (on d8). In such an overwhelmingly winning endgame, Black’s goal is to keep checking the white king and steadily drive it into further trouble.

One promising idea is to use the queen to deliver a forcing check while avoiding any blunders. For example, if Black plays Qe7 (moving from e5 to e7), that does deliver a check by the queen (since the white king on d8 is diagonally adjacent to e7). However, that move would be a blunder because the white king could simply capture the queen on e7 (d8→e7 is a legal king move) and win back the queen. Clearly, we must avoid any move that allows the king to capture our queen.

Instead, consider moving the queen from e5 to d6. The move Qd6 (UCI move: e5d6) uses the queen along the d‑file so that the white king on d8 is in check. After Qd6+, the white king’s legal moves are limited. Checking Qd6, White cannot step to d7, c7, or e7 (as these are attacked by the queen along the file or diagonally). The king’s only options become c8 or e8. Importantly, neither of these adjacent squares enables the white king to capture the queen on d6 (since d6 is not adjacent to either c8 or e8).

Because Qd6+ is both forcing and safe, it is a strong move for Black that continues to press the winning advantage.

I’ll now play this move.

make_move e5d6

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, one promising candidate is to check with the queen while keeping it out of reach of the white king. For example, notice that the black queen is on g1 while the white king sits on f3. If we drop the queen down to f1, then the queen along the f‐file will deliver a check yet will not be immediately capturable by the white king (since f1 isn’t adjacent to f3). 

Thus, a strong move is to play:

  make_move g1f1

This move gives check along the f‑file and forces the white king to move (its only escape squares appear to be e3, e4, g3, or g4). Moving the white king will further restrict its position, making it easier for you to eventually coordinate your king and queen for a winning mating attack.

I’ll now play:

make_move g1f1

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board:

8 | ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ♚ ⭘
7 | ♟ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ♟ ♟ ♟
6 | ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘
5 | ♟ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ♟ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘
4 | ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ♔ ⭘
3 | ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘
2 | ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘
1 | ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ♛ ⭘ ⭘
    a  b  c  d  e  f  g  h

We see that:
• Black’s king is on g8.
• Black’s queen is on f1.
• Black pawns are on a7, f7, g7, h7, a5, and e5.
• White’s only piece is the king on g4.

In endgames of king and queen versus lone king—with some extra pawns on the board—it is usually best to deliver checks that restrict the enemy king’s escape routes while keeping your queen defended (so that your opponent cannot capture it).

One very forceful candidate move here is to play Qf1–f4. (UCI notation: “f1f4”.)

Why Qf4? Let’s see:
• Moving the queen from f1 to f4 is legal along the f-file, as f2 and f3 are empty.
• On f4, the queen gives a direct check to the white king on g4—indeed, g4 lies diagonally from f4.
• After Qf4, the white king’s available squares are severely reduced. A quick look:
  – White’s adjacent squares from g4 are f3, g3, h3, f4, h4, f5, g5, and h5.
  – Under check from a queen on f4, many of these are covered. For example, note that:
   • f3, f4, g5 are attacked along the file, rank, or diagonal.
   • Moreover, the pawn on e5 defends f4 (it “controls” that square by its diagonal attack), so the white king cannot capture the queen.
• With Qf4, the white king is forced only to consider moves like h3 or h5, which greatly limits its mobility.

Thus, Qf4 is a strong, forcing move that maintains the initiative and puts immediate pressure on the lone white king.

I will now execute this move.

make_move f1f4

If Black plays Qxf2+, then White’s king on e1 will have no legal move except to capture the queen (since all adjacent squares are blocked by its own pieces). Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board, I’ve examined our options. One very forceful idea is to use our queen, currently on f1, to give a check without being immediately capturable. Moving the queen from f1 to g1 (UCI move “f1g1”) places it on the g‐file so that it checks White’s king on g5 (since the queen on g1 controls the entire g‑file: g2, g3, g4, g5, etc.). This check forces White’s king to move (it cannot capture our queen since the queen is safely tucked away on g1) and improves our initiative.

I’ll therefore play:

make_move f1g1

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board configuration, one strong candidate is to bring the queen into an active checking position. For instance, moving the queen from G1 to G6 (which in UCI is "g1g6") not only delivers a check on the white king along rank 6 but also forces the white king to move into a more confined set of squares. 

Here’s a brief look at the idea:

• The queen travels vertically from G1 to G6 (path squares G2, G3, G4, G5 are empty).
• Once on G6, the queen is placed on the 6th rank. Because the white king is on E6, it comes under immediate horizontal threat.
• With white’s only piece being the king, forcing it to move limits its options and helps build toward a decisive mating net.

Thus, I will now make the move:

make_move g1g6
